var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.jl","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Hypertext templating DSL for Julia","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Define HTML-like templates that compile to plain Julia functions. Use looping, pattern matching, conditions, interpolation, slots, and composition.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Basic-Usage","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Basic Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Valid HTML syntax is valid template syntax in HypertextTemplates.jl. If you know HTML then you're already part-way to knowing how to use this package. Here's a really simple template function defined in a file called template.html.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function example>\n  <p>A really basic template</p>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"We define a template function with a <function> tag. The first attribute is it's name. Note that these names are case-insensitive, so example is the same as Example.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Any tags and content within the <function> tag are what is shown when you render the template.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Template functions are defined in .html files which can be are imported into any Julia code using the exported template\"<file name>\" string macro provided by this package. <file name> is the path to a valid .html file containing one or more template functions.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"So we can import a template into a Julia module with","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"module MyTemplates\n\nusing HypertextTemplates\n\ntemplate\"path/to/template.html\"\n\nend","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"And then we can convert it to a String with","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"julia> text = render(MyTemplates.example)\n\"<p>A really basic template</p>\"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Our-Second-Template","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Our Second Template","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Let's add a new template function to that template.html file:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function second-template count=\"1::Integer\" value>\n  <ul>\n    <for iter=\"1:count\" item>\n      <li><span .julia=item></span>: <span .julia=value></span></li>\n    </for>\n  </ul>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"There's several concepts to unpack in this template, which we'll cover below.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Naming-Conventions","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Naming Conventions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"We've used \"kebab-case\" for the naming. You'll need to reference from Julia with MyTemplates.var\"second-template\" since it's not a valid Julia identifier. You are free to use \"snake-case\" instead if you like though. Don't use \"camel-case\" though, since the template names are case-insensitive, as mentioned above.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Template-Props","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Template Props","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"There are two properties (or \"props\", to steal from the JavaScript world). The first, count, is optional and defaults to the value 1. It is also restricted to Integer types. If you pass a non-Integer to this template function it will throw a TypeError. The second prop is called value and has no default value (or type) so it must be given a value (of any type) when calling the template function.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Iteration","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Iteration","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"In the body of this template we are building up an unordered list of items to render. We use a <for> tag for that. It takes two, or three props. iter is the \"iterable\" object to loop over. This can, as the name implies, be any Julia object that supports iteration. item declares the name of the iteration variable that will contain each item iterated over in iter. item is equivalent to writing item=item or item=\"item\" and is just shorthand to avoid repetition. If you want to use a different name for the iteration variable then just write item=\"whatever-you-want\".","category":"page"},{"location":"#Interpolation","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Interpolation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Inside the loop we build the list item, which is the built of two <julia> value interpolations. We pass the item iteration variable as the first, and the value prop as the second.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Using-Templates","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Using Templates","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"We've seen one way to get the output of a template function, via the render function. That's useful, but you'll likely want to compose templates to create more complex hypertext and avoid repetition.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"You can use one of your template functions in another template with:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function third-template number>\n  <example></example>\n  <second-template count=\"number\" value='\"Hello, world!\"'></second-template>\n  <second-template count=\"2 * number\" value='\"Goodbye, world!\"'></second-template>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"So we just use our custom template functions as if they are HTML tags and pass their props as the attributes. Note that because we can \"call\" our templates as if they are HTML tags, we cannot name our templates the same as any valid HTML (or SVG) tag name. You'll see an error if you try to do so.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"We could then render third-template with","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"julia> render(MyTemplates.var\"third-template\"; number = 2)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Whole-File-Templates","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Whole-File Templates","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"So far we've seen how to build \"partial\" templates, which are templates that only render part of a complete HTML document. You'll want to be able to render complete documents though if you want to do anything useful with them.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"To do that we can create a .html file and start it with a single <html> tag that contains out complete content. The name of the template will be derived from the file name. For example a file named path/to/base-template.html will be called <base-template> in other templates that it is used in, and var\"base-template\" in Julia code.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<html lang=\"en\">\n  <head>\n    <title $julia=\"My Website - $(props.title)\"></title>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <third-example number=\"props.number\"></third-example>\n  </body>\n</html>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Since a whole-file template does not explicitly declare it's props you reference them via the props object that is made available within the template definition. Currently no optional or typed props are supported here.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Conditional-Rendering","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Conditional Rendering","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"You can conditionally render part of a template with the <show> tag. It has a single prop called when which is a Julia expression that evaluates to true or false, e.g.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<show when=\"isodd(number)\">\n  <p>The number is odd.</p>\n</show>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"A <fallback> can be provided for when the when claus is false.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<show when=\"isodd(number)\">\n  <p>The number is odd.</p>\n  <fallback>\n    <p><em>The number is even!</em></p>\n  </fallback>\n</show>","category":"page"},{"location":"#Pattern-Matching","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Pattern Matching","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"More complex conditional should instead be written using the <match> tag since it scales much better than nesting <show> tags. It supports the same syntax as the Match.jl package since it uses that package internally.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function matcher-template number>\n  <match value=\"number\">\n    <case when=\"1\">\n      <p>The number is one.</p>\n    </case>\n    <case when=\"::AbstractString\">\n      <strong>The number is actually a string!</strong>\n    </case>\n    <case when=\"[element]\">\n      <p>\n        The number is actually a single element vector containing:\n        <span .julia=element></span>\n      </p>\n    </case>\n    <case when=\"_\">\n      <p>The number is something else.</p>\n    </case>\n  </match>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Check out the documentation for the Match.jl package. @match and <match> have equivalent features.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Slots","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Slots","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"So far all the custom template function we have defined have just taken a collection of props and performed their rendering based on that. More complex requirements will likely need you to render templates \"around\" other content. For that we use <slot> tags.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function slot-example>\n  <div class=\"...\">\n    <h1>Header</h1>\n    <slot></slot>\n    <hr />\n    <p>Footer</p>\n  </div>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Note the <slot />. We can now use this slot-example template as follows:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<slot-example>\n  <p>Content that will appear between the header and the footer.</p>\n</slot-example>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"We can also have more complex requirements that need multiple different slots rendered in a single template function. For that we have named slots:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function named-slots-example>\n  <div class=\"...\">\n    <h1>Header</h1>\n    <slot content></slot>\n    <hr />\n    <p><slot footer></slot></p>\n  </div>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"And then we'll use it with","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<named-slots-example>\n  <em:footer>Footer content goes here</em:footer>\n  <p:content>The body content</p:content>\n</named-slots-example>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Note that the usage of the slots can be defined in a different order to that in which they will be rendered if needed. Try to avoid this if possible though for the sake of clarity.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Props-vs.-Attributes","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Props vs. Attributes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"HTML elements have attributes. Template functions have props. The difference is that attributes are static and will appear in the rendered result exactly as they are in template definition. E.g.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function props-vs-attributes foo>\n  <p class=\"foo\"></p>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"This will render as follows since class is static on a <p> element.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"julia> render(Templates.var\"props-vs-attributes\"; foo=\"my-css-class\")\n\"<p class=\\\"foo\\\"></p>\"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"If instead you need the class to be dynamic and render whatever foo happens to contain then prefix the attribute with a . as follows:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function props-vs-attributes-dynamic foo>\n  <p .class=\"foo\"></p>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"This will render as follows since class is static on a <p> element.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"julia> render(Templates.var\"props-vs-attributes-dynamic\"; foo=\"my-css-class\")\n\"<p class=\\\"my-css-class\\\"></p>\"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"If you would like to instead just construct a string attribute based on some interpolated Julia values then prefixing the attribute with a $ will do that for you.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"<function edit-contact-link id>\n  <a $href=\"/contact/$id/edit\">Edit</a>\n</function>","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"This will render as follows:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"julia> render(Templates.var\"edit-contact-link\"; id=123)\n\"<a href=\\\"/contact/123/edit\\\">Edit</a>\"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Markdown-Template-Files","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Markdown Template Files","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Experimental Feature","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"You can also use Markdown files as templates. This requires the user to have imported the CommonMark package prior to using a markdown file in a template macro. Internally the markdown syntax is rendered to HTML using CommonMark.jl's html function and then parsed into a template function using HypertextTemplates.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Extensions are enabled by default in the CommonMark parser, such as tables, admonitions, and footnotes. Since CommonMark supports embedding some basic HTML tags you can also use those in your markdown templates to call other HTML or markdown templates for composition. Don't expect complete HTML support to work though, and if you find yourself embedding large amounts of HTML in your markdown templates then you should probably just use HTML templates instead and then embed that custom template tag in your markdown template.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"TOML frontmatter syntax is used to allow the template name and props to be declared. When no name is provided the template name will be derived from the file name. When no props are provided the template will have no props. Frontmatter is optional and declared with +++ fences at the top of the file.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"+++\nname = \"my-template\"\nprops = [\"foo\", \"bar\"]\n+++\n\n<large-custom-template prop=\"foo\"></large-custom-template>\n\n# My Template\n\nThis is a template that takes two props: `foo` and `bar`. Their values are\n<span julia=\"foo\"></span> and <span julia=\"bar\"></span> respectively.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Development-vs.-Production-Usage","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Development vs. Production Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"HypertextTemplates supports integration with Revise-based development workflows.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"During development when you are editing your templates iteratively to test out different layouts and styling you'll likely want your templates to automatically update after editing them without having to re-evaluate templates. If you have Revise loaded in your session this will happen automatically based on whether the template file has been edited since it was last called. You don't need to do anything special aside from ensuring you are running Revise, which you probably already are.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Note that this does add a small amount of overhead. For production builds of your code you should ensure that Revise is not part of your build. If you do this then all templates will be run without checking for updated file contents.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Template-Lookup","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Template Lookup","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"During development you'll likely need to find the source file and line number of particular parts of the rendered HTML. This is usually done by searching the codebase for matching tag or attribute names with an editor's search feature. This becomes tedious though, so HypertextTemplates provides a \"template lookup\" feature that allows you to jump to the source file and line number of any part of the rendered HTML by hovering over it in the browser and pressing Ctrl+Shift.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"To set this up you'll need to have Revise loaded in your session, as you should if you're in a development setting. Doing this will automatically annotate all rendered HTML with special data-htloc attributes that contain the source file and line number of the template that rendered that part of the HTML. Secondly, you'll need to add the TemplateFileLookup middleware to the HTTP server that is serving your rendered HTML.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"using HypertextTemplates\nusing HTTP\n\nHTTP.serve(router |> TemplateFileLookup, host, port)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Now just hover your mouse over any part of your browser and press Ctrl+Shift. This will open your editor at the correct file and line number. You'll need to have set the \"EDITOR\" environment variable to your editor command in your ENV in your ~/.julia/config/startup.jl file for this to work. See the Julia manual for more details on setting environment variables.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Public-Interface","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"Public Interface","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.jl","text":"Modules = [HypertextTemplates]","category":"page"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.TemplateFileLookup-Tuple{Any}","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.TemplateFileLookup","text":"TemplateFileLookup(handler)\n\nThis is a developer tool that can be added to an HTTP handler stack to allow the user to open the template file in their default editor by holding down the Ctrl key and clicking on the rendered template. This is useful for debugging navigating the template files instead of having to manually search through a codebase for the template file that renders a given item within a page.\n\nHTTP.serve(router |> TemplateFileLookup, host, port)\n\nAlways add the TemplateFileLookup handler after the other handlers, since it needs to inject a script into the response to listen for clicks on the rendered template.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.render-Tuple{Any, Vararg{Any}}","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.render","text":"render(template, args...; kws...)\n\nRender a template to a string. args and kws are passed to the template function and a String is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.slots","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.slots","text":"slots([unnamed]; named...)\n\nHelper function to construct NamedTuples to pass to templates as their slots.\n\nThis function is useful when composing template functions within Julia code rather than within template files templates. For example when rendering a markdown template with a specific wrapper layout.\n\nbase_layout(stdout, slots(markdown(; title = \"My Title\")))\n\nThe above does several things:\n\nDelays the rendering of the markdown template until the base_layout template requests rendering within it's unnamed slot.\nCreates the slots object to assign the delayed markdown template to the unnamed slot.\nRenders the base_layout template to stdout with the slots object, which will render the markdown template within the unnamed slot.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.@create_template_str","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.@create_template_str","text":"create_template\"folder/file.html\"\n\nA helper macro to create an empty template file. The string must be a path to a non-existant HTML file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"macro"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.@custom_element-Tuple{Any}","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.@custom_element","text":"@custom_element \"custom-element-name\"\n\nDefine a name for a custom element. This is a tag in the HTML templates that simply prints itself back out rather than calling a defined template function, or printing a valid HTML tag.\n\nThe @custom_element macro does not provide the definition of the custom element itself, and is only used to allow rendering the tag of the custom element in a rendered template.\n\nSee Web Components documentation for more information on custom elements and how they are used.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"macro"},{"location":"#HypertextTemplates.@template_str","page":"HypertextTemplates.jl","title":"HypertextTemplates.@template_str","text":"template\"folder/file.html\"\n\nDefine an HTML template. The string must be a path to a valid HTML file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"macro"}]
}
